        body: '<p><strong>Never trust, always verify:</strong> Implicit trust based on network location is removed. A device on the internal network is not automatically trusted — it must authenticate and be authorized for each resource it accesses.</p><p><strong>Assume breach:</strong> Design security as if attackers are already inside. Segment systems, limit lateral movement, and monitor all traffic — including east-west (internal-to-internal) traffic, not just north-south (in/out) traffic.</p><p><strong>Least privilege:</strong> Every user, device, and service gets only the access it needs for its specific function. Excessive permissions expand the attack surface and the potential blast radius of any compromise.</p><p><strong>Continuous verification:</strong> Trust is dynamic, not static. A session trusted five minutes ago may require re-verification if context changes — for example, if the user\'s location shifts or they attempt to access a more sensitive resource.</p>',
