        body: '<p><strong>Honeypot:</strong> A decoy system configured to attract attackers. It mimics a real server, service, or application — but contains no real data or production workloads. Any connection to the honeypot is suspicious by definition. Honeypots allow security teams to observe attacker techniques, tools, and behaviors in a controlled environment without risk to production systems.</p><p><strong>Honeynet:</strong> A network of multiple honeypots. Real networks include servers, workstations, routers, switches, and firewalls — a honeynet replicates this complexity to appear more convincing. Multiple data sources from multiple honeypot devices provide much richer attacker intelligence than a single honeypot can offer.</p><p>Both are designed to appear as attractive, accessible targets — running services that look vulnerable, containing data that appears valuable — while creating no actual risk to real operations.</p>',
