        body: '<p>Data at rest sits on storage devices — hard drives, SSDs, USB drives, or cloud storage. It is vulnerable to physical theft, unauthorized access, or insider threats.</p><p><strong>Full-disk encryption (FDE):</strong> Encrypts the entire storage device including the operating system, applications, and all user data. Examples: <em>BitLocker</em> (Windows, often backed by TPM) and <em>FileVault</em> (macOS). Transparent to the user once unlocked — protects against physical drive theft.</p><p><strong>File-level / volume encryption:</strong> Encrypts individual files, folders, or storage volumes rather than the entire disk. Examples: <em>EFS (Encrypting File System)</em> on Windows and third-party tools. More granular — encrypt specific sensitive files while leaving the rest of the disk normally accessible.</p>',
