        body: '<p><strong>Out-of-band key exchange</strong> avoids the problem by sharing the key through a completely separate channel from the one being secured. Examples: delivering a key on a USB drive in person, sharing a key verbally over an encrypted phone call, or using a courier. This is highly secure but impractical at internet scale — you cannot hand-deliver a key to every web server you visit.</p><p><strong>In-band key exchange</strong> transmits the key over the same network as the encrypted data, but protects the key using asymmetric encryption. The sender encrypts the symmetric key with the recipient\'s public key and sends it. Only the recipient\'s private key can decrypt it. This is how the TLS handshake works — the session key is exchanged securely over an untrusted public network.</p>',
