        body: '<p>A blockchain is composed of <strong>blocks</strong>, each containing a set of transactions or records plus the <em>hash of the previous block</em>. This hash reference creates the "chain" — each block is cryptographically linked to all blocks before it.</p><p>If an attacker tries to alter a historical block, its hash changes. The changed hash breaks the link to the next block, which references the old (now incorrect) hash. To fix this, the attacker must recalculate every subsequent block — and do so faster than the entire distributed network is adding new legitimate blocks. In a large network, this is computationally infeasible.</p><p>The ledger is <strong>distributed</strong> — every participant (node) maintains a full, synchronized copy. There is no single authoritative server to attack. <strong>Consensus mechanisms</strong> (Proof of Work, Proof of Stake) ensure all nodes agree on which version of the chain is valid.</p>',
