        type: 'concept',
        title: 'Security Properties and Applications',
        body: '<p>Blockchain provides three key security properties for recorded data:</p><p><strong>Integrity:</strong> The hash chain makes any historical modification detectable across all copies — all subsequent blocks would have wrong hashes.</p><p><strong>Transparency:</strong> The ledger is visible to all participants — every transaction is auditable by any node at any time.</p><p><strong>Immutability:</strong> Once a block is confirmed by sufficient consensus, it is effectively permanent. Reversing it would require controlling the majority of the network\'s computing power.</p><p><strong>Applications beyond cryptocurrency:</strong></p><p><strong>Payment processing:</strong> Bitcoin, Ethereum — decentralized value transfer without intermediaries.</p><p><strong>Digital identification:</strong> Self-sovereign identity — users control verifiable credentials without relying on a central authority.</p><p><strong>Supply chain monitoring:</strong> Track goods from origin to patient/consumer — immutable provenance records prevent fraud.</p><p><strong>Digital voting:</strong> Tamper-evident election records — each vote is a transaction that cannot be altered after submission.</p>',
