        a: 'B — The old certificate must be revoked by the CA — added to the CRL or marked revoked in the OCSP system. Revocation tells clients that this certificate should no longer be trusted even though its validity period has not expired. Clients checking certificate status (via CRL download or OCSP query) will see the revocation status and refuse to trust the certificate. (A) Certificates are immutable — you cannot change fields in an issued certificate. (C) Reissuing with a new serial number would create a new certificate — the old one still needs explicit revocation. (D) Rebooting the server with a new certificate does nothing to inform clients that the old certificate is compromised.',
