        body: '<p>Social engineers exploit predictable human psychology. The six main motivational triggers used to manipulate targets into complying with illegitimate requests are:</p><ul><li><strong>Authority</strong> — People comply when a request appears to come from someone with legitimate power (IT manager, CEO, government official, auditor). Attackers impersonate authority figures to bypass skepticism.</li><li><strong>Urgency</strong> — Creating a compelling sense of time pressure prevents the target from pausing to verify. "Your account will be locked in 10 minutes" forces rapid, unconsidered action.</li><li><strong>Social proof</strong> — People look to what others are doing to determine the right action. "Everyone in accounting has already updated their password" implies non-compliance is the outlier.</li><li><strong>Scarcity</strong> — The perception that an opportunity is limited or running out increases psychological pressure. "Only two vouchers left" or "This offer expires today."</li><li><strong>Likability</strong> — Targets are more likely to comply with people they like — through shared interests, flattery, or simulated friendship. Attackers build rapport before making the malicious request.</li><li><strong>Fear</strong> — Threats of negative consequences (account suspension, legal action, data exposure) compel victims to act to avoid the feared outcome. "If you do not verify now, your account will be permanently deleted."</li></ul><p>Recognizing these triggers is the first step to resisting them. Security awareness training should teach employees to pause and verify whenever they feel any of these pressures.</p>',
