        body: '<p><strong>Reflection</strong> — The attacker spoofs the victim\'s IP address as the source when sending requests to innocent third-party servers. The third-party servers send their replies to the victim (not the attacker), flooding the victim with traffic while the attacker remains hidden.</p><p><strong>Amplification</strong> — Protocols that produce large responses to small requests are ideal for amplification. NTP (Network Time Protocol) monlist command can amplify a 234-byte request into a 48KB response (200× amplification). DNS and ICMP are also commonly abused.</p><p><strong>Why it works</strong> — These protocols have little or no authentication. The attacker turns legitimate internet services against the victim using minimal bandwidth on their end to generate massive traffic at the target.</p>',
