        type: 'concept',
        title: 'Protocol and Application-Layer DoS',
        body: '<p><strong>Protocol attacks (Layer 4)</strong> — Exploit weaknesses in transport-layer protocols rather than consuming bandwidth.</p><p><strong>SYN flood</strong> — The attacker sends a large volume of TCP SYN packets with spoofed source IPs. The server responds to each with a SYN-ACK and waits for the final ACK that never arrives. Each half-open connection consumes a slot in the server connection state table. When the table fills, the server cannot accept any new legitimate connections — even though bandwidth is barely used. Defense: SYN cookies (server encodes state in the sequence number rather than the connection table, so no table entry is needed until the handshake completes).</p><p><strong>Application-layer attacks (Layer 7)</strong> — Target the application rather than network bandwidth or protocol state. Because requests look like legitimate traffic, they bypass volumetric defenses.</p><ul><li><strong>HTTP flood</strong> — High-rate GET or POST requests to resource-intensive pages (search, login, cart checkout). Each request triggers expensive back-end processing.</li><li><strong>Slowloris</strong> — Opens many HTTP connections and sends partial headers slowly, keeping connections alive without completing the request. Web servers have a limited connection pool — Slowloris exhausts it with a very low bandwidth requirement.</li></ul><p><strong>L7 defenses</strong> — Rate limiting per IP, CAPTCHA challenges, WAF (Web Application Firewall) behavioral rules, and CDN DDoS scrubbing services.</p>',
