        body: '<p><strong>Evil Twin AP</strong> — A rogue access point configured with the same SSID (network name) as a legitimate AP. The attacker broadcasts a stronger signal so devices automatically connect to the evil twin instead of the real AP. All traffic flows through the attacker, enabling credential capture, session hijacking, and SSL stripping. Commonly deployed in public spaces (coffee shops, airports) where users freely join open networks.</p><p><strong>WPS (Wi-Fi Protected Setup) PIN attack</strong> — WPS was designed to simplify device pairing via an 8-digit PIN. The PIN is verified in two halves (4+4 digits), reducing the keyspace to about 11,000 combinations — trivially brute-forced. Tools like Reaver and Pixie Dust can recover the WPS PIN and therefore the WPA2 passphrase even on networks with strong passwords. Defense: disable WPS entirely on all access points.</p><p><strong>KRACK (Key Reinstallation Attack)</strong> — A 2017 attack against the WPA2 4-way handshake. By replaying and manipulating handshake messages, an attacker forces a client to reinstall an already-used encryption key with a zeroed nonce. This allows decryption, replay, and potentially injection of traffic. Mitigated by patching both access points and client devices. WPA3 is not vulnerable to KRACK.</p>',
