        body: '<p><strong>Birthday attack</strong> — Exploits the birthday paradox: in a group of 23 people, there is a 50% chance two share a birthday. In cryptography, this translates to finding two different inputs that produce the same hash value (a collision) much faster than brute force would suggest.</p><p><strong>Hash collision</strong> — Two different plaintexts produce the same hash digest. This breaks the integrity guarantee of hashing because a malicious document could produce the same hash as a legitimate one.</p><p><strong>MD5 weakness</strong> — MD5 (Message Digest 5, 1992) had theoretical collision vulnerabilities identified in 1996. By December 2008, researchers demonstrated creating a fake CA certificate that appeared legitimate under MD5 verification — allowing them to sign fraudulent certificates trusted by all browsers. MD5 is now considered cryptographically broken.</p><p><strong>Defense</strong> — Use hash algorithms with large output sizes (SHA-256, SHA-3) to make birthday attacks computationally infeasible.</p>',
