        body: '<p><strong>Replay attack</strong> — An attacker intercepts a valid authentication or transaction message and retransmits it later to gain unauthorized access or repeat a transaction. The message itself is legitimate; the problem is that it is being reused out of context. Example: capturing a Kerberos ticket and submitting it again from a different machine.</p><p><strong>Defense against replay attacks — Nonces</strong>: A nonce (number used once) is a unique random value included in each authentication challenge. Because the nonce changes with every request, a replayed message from a prior session will fail — the server considers the nonce already consumed. Timestamps further limit the replay window to a few minutes.</p><p><strong>IV (Initialization Vector) attack</strong> — Many block cipher modes (CBC, CTR) require a unique IV to randomize the ciphertext so that identical plaintexts produce different ciphertexts. WEP (Wired Equivalent Privacy) used only a 24-bit IV. In any busy wireless network, IVs must be recycled after ~16 million packets. By collecting enough packets encrypted with the same IV, an attacker can statistically recover the WEP keystream and then the key. This IV-reuse vulnerability is the core reason WEP was deprecated in favor of WPA2 and WPA3.</p>',
