        body: '<p><strong>Pass-the-Hash (PtH)</strong> — A technique that captures an NTLM password hash from Windows memory and uses it directly to authenticate to other systems — without ever knowing or cracking the underlying plaintext password. Windows NTLM authentication transmits the hash rather than the password, so an attacker who extracts the hash from LSASS memory (using tools like Mimikatz) can impersonate the user across the network.</p><p><strong>PtH mitigations:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>Credential Guard</strong> — Isolates LSASS in a virtualization-based security container, preventing hash extraction from memory.</li><li><strong>LAPS (Local Administrator Password Solution)</strong> — Ensures each machine has a unique, randomly generated local admin password, limiting lateral movement even if one hash is captured.</li><li><strong>Disable NTLM</strong> — Enforce Kerberos authentication where possible; NTLM is the protocol PtH exploits.</li><li><strong>MFA</strong> — An additional factor that PtH alone cannot satisfy.</li></ul><p><strong>Credential stuffing</strong> — Attackers take username/password pairs leaked in public data breaches and automatically test them against other services at scale. Credential stuffing exploits password reuse — a breach at one site exposes accounts at every other site where the same credentials are used.</p><p><strong>Credential stuffing mitigations:</strong> MFA stops stuffing even when credentials match. Password managers encourage unique passwords per service. Credential breach monitoring (integrated Have I Been Pwned alerts) notifies users when their credentials appear in breach data.</p>',
