        body: '<p><strong>UPS (Uninterruptible Power Supply)</strong> — Provides immediate short-term backup power during blackouts, brownouts, and power surges. Bridges the gap between a power outage and generator start-up.</p><p><strong>UPS types:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>Offline / Standby UPS</strong> — Normally passes utility power directly; switches to battery on failure. Brief transfer delay during switch.</li><li><strong>Line-interactive UPS</strong> — Conditions incoming power (handles brownouts and surges); switches to battery for complete failures. Better power conditioning than standby.</li><li><strong>Online / Double-conversion UPS</strong> — Always converts power through the battery — incoming AC → DC (charges battery) → DC → AC (to equipment). Zero transfer time on failure. Best isolation from power quality issues. Most expensive.</li></ul><p><strong>UPS features</strong> — Automatic shutdown (safely powers down systems if battery depletes), battery capacity (determines runtime), outlet quantity, phone/network line surge suppression.</p>',
