        body: '<p>APIs (Application Programming Interfaces) are the integration layer for modern security automation — scripts communicate with firewalls, SIEMs, cloud platforms, and identity providers through API calls. Securing APIs is therefore a core security operations concern.</p><p><strong>API authentication methods:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>API keys</strong> — A secret token included in each request (header or query parameter). Simple to implement but must be treated like a password — stored in secrets managers, rotated regularly, and never committed to source control.</li><li><strong>OAuth 2.0 scopes</strong> — Grant the automation token only the minimum permissions needed (least privilege). A script that only reads firewall logs should not have a token with write access.</li><li><strong>Service accounts and certificates</strong> — Dedicated non-human identities with defined roles; client certificates provide mutual authentication.</li></ul><p><strong>API security controls:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>Rate limiting</strong> — Limit requests per time window to prevent abuse and brute force of API endpoints.</li><li><strong>API gateway</strong> — A centralized proxy that enforces authentication, authorization, rate limiting, logging, and TLS termination for all API traffic. Provides a single enforcement point.</li><li><strong>Input validation</strong> — APIs must validate and sanitize all input — they are subject to the same injection attacks (SQL injection, command injection) as web applications.</li><li><strong>HTTPS only</strong> — All API traffic must be encrypted in transit; never expose API keys over HTTP.</li></ul>',
